###Writing an equation

Since Jamie is going to run for $\goldE{\dfrac12}$ of an hour, let's substitute that for $\goldE{\text{time}}$. Then, we can solve for $\maroonD{\text{distance }(d)}$ in terms of $\blueE{\text{rate }(r)}$:

$\begin{align}
\blueE{\text{rate}} &= \dfrac{\maroonD{\text{distance}}}{\goldE{\text{time}}}
\\\\
\blueE{r} &= \dfrac{\maroonD{d}}{\goldE{\dfrac12}}
\\\\
\dfrac12 \cdot \blueE{r} &= \dfrac{\maroonD{d}}{\cancel{\goldE{\dfrac12}} }\cdot \cancel{\dfrac12}
\\\\
\dfrac12 \blueE{r} &= \maroonD{d}
\\\\
\maroonD{d} &= \dfrac12 \blueE{r}
\end{align}$

###Strategy

We can find $n\%$ of a number like this:

$\begin{align}
\goldE{n}\% \text{ of }(\maroonD{\text{whole}}) &= \blueE{\text{part}}
\\\\
\dfrac{\goldE{n}}{100} \cdot \maroonD{\text{whole}} &= \blueE{\text{part}}
\end{align}$

We know that the discount is $15\%$. If we identify the part and the whole, we can write a general equation that relates the amount of discount ($d$) to the usual price ($p$).

Then, we can find the amount of discount Dominic receives on an item whose usual price is $\pounds 80$.

###Writing an equation

Our $\maroonD{\text{whole}}$ is the usual price $\maroonD{p}$, and the $\blueE{\text{part}}$ is the amount of discount Dominic receives ($\blueE{d}$) with the $\goldE{15}\%$ discount:

$\begin{align}
\dfrac{\goldE{n}}{100} \cdot \maroonD{\text{whole}} &= \blueE{\text{part}}
\\\\
\dfrac{\goldE{15}}{100} \cdot \maroonD{p} &= \blueE{d}
\\\\
0.15 \maroonD{p} &= \blueE{d}
\\\\
\blueE{d} &= 0.15 \maroonD{p}
\end{align}$

